00:00:00.790 --> 00:00:04.700
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington D.C.

00:00:06.220 --> 00:00:07.520
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: This afternoon,

00:00:07.520 --> 00:00:09.840
my guest is a celebrated
novelist and poet Ha Jin.

00:00:09.840 --> 00:00:11.400
Thank you so much for coming today.

00:00:11.400 --> 00:00:12.700
&gt;&gt; Ha Jin: Oh, thank you.

00:00:12.700 --> 00:00:14.500
I'm happy to be here again.

00:00:14.500 --> 00:00:17.090
[ Applause ]

00:00:17.090 --> 00:00:18.860
Thank you.

00:00:18.860 --> 00:00:21.170
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: The life of this
remarkable writer began in China

00:00:21.170 --> 00:00:23.080
where his father was
a military officer.

00:00:23.080 --> 00:00:26.430
At 13, Ha Jin himself joined
the People's Liberation Army

00:00:26.430 --> 00:00:28.400
which he stayed with
until he was 19.

00:00:28.400 --> 00:00:30.790
He earned a Masters degree
in Literature in China,

00:00:30.790 --> 00:00:35.400 position:56%
and earned a scholarship to Brandeis
University in the late 1980s.

00:00:35.400 --> 00:00:38.650
When he and the rest of world
watched the Chinese government

00:00:38.650 --> 00:00:42.740
murder democracy demonstrators
in Tiananmen Square in 1989,

00:00:42.740 --> 00:00:45.450
he decided to remain
in the United States.

00:00:45.450 --> 00:00:48.270 position:56%
He eventually earned a PhD, and now,
he teaches at Boston University.

00:00:48.270 --> 00:00:51.910
Over the years, he's published
several unforgettable novels

00:00:51.910 --> 00:00:54.720
about life in China and the
immigrant experience in America.

00:00:54.720 --> 00:00:56.020
He's won a number of awards,

00:00:56.020 --> 00:01:01.010 position:56%
including two PEN/Faulkner awards
including for one called "War Trash"

00:01:01.010 --> 00:01:04.850
which was also a finalist
for the Pulitzer Prize.

00:01:04.850 --> 00:01:07.440
His new novel is called
"The Boat Rocker".

00:01:07.440 --> 00:01:11.300
It's a story of a Chinese
patriot named Feng Danlin?

00:01:11.300 --> 00:01:12.600
&gt;&gt; Ha Jin: Yes.

00:01:12.600 --> 00:01:13.900
&gt;&gt; Ron Charles: Okay.

00:01:13.900 --> 00:01:16.470
Who works in New York as a
reporter for a news service

00:01:16.470 --> 00:01:19.630
that appeals primarily to
Chinese people living abroad.

00:01:19.630 --> 00:01:23.230
And, Danlin is so passionate
about exposing what he calls

00:01:23.230 --> 00:01:27.460
"the towering corruption of Chinese
politics" with his acid tongue

00:01:27.460 --> 00:01:30.090
and his heart stabbing commentary.

00:01:30.090 --> 00:01:34.260
His personal credo is
"Honesty is strength.

00:01:34.260 --> 00:01:36.010
Democracy dies in darkness."

00:01:36.010 --> 00:01:37.810
[ Laughter ]

00:01:37.810 --> 00:01:41.630
[ Applause ]

